          "body": "The Passover of 5:10 is the first celebration of the feast in the promised land. The last Passover clearly recorded before this was at Sinai (Numbers 9:1-5), thirty-nine years earlier. The precision of the date — fourteenth of the first month, at evening — matches the Mosaic prescription exactly (Exodus 12:6). The theological argument is structural: the Exodus that Passover commemorates is not completed until the people are in the land. Israel at Passover in Canaan is Israel declaring that the deliverance from Egypt has reached its destination. The manna that ceases the day after (5:12) confirms this: it was wilderness provision, and wilderness is over. The unleavened cakes and parched grain of 5:11 are the first fruits of the land — the promise sworn in 5:6 ('a land flowing with milk and honey') is now tasted. Peter Davids's observation about James 1:3 applies here with equal force: the testing produces endurance, and endurance completes what was begun. Forty years of tested, refined, wilderness-formed faith now eats the produce of the promise. The new provision does not supersede the covenant; it fulfills it."
