          "body": "The theophany of 5:13-15 is among the most theologically dense encounters in the entire Former Prophets. Joshua approaches a figure with a drawn sword — a posture of active readiness, not neutrality — and asks the binary question: 'For us or for our adversaries?' The commander refuses the binary entirely: 'No; rather I indeed come now as captain of the host of the LORD.' This is not a refusal to take sides; it is a correction of the question. Joshua had framed the situation as Israel's war in which God might or might not be an ally. The commander reframes it: this is Yahweh's war in which Israel is the human instrument. The identity of this figure has occupied commentators for centuries. The direct parallel to the burning bush — same command (remove your sandals), same declaration (holy ground), same prostrate response — marks him as the Angel of Yahweh who appears throughout the patriarchal narratives (Genesis 16:7-13; 22:11-18; Exodus 3:2-6), identified with Yahweh yet distinct — what orthodox Trinitarian exegesis from Justin Martyr through Calvin to contemporary evangelical scholarship (cf. Gordon Wenham, Tremper Longman III) has read as a pre-incarnate Christophany. The chapter ends without a battle plan. Joshua has removed his sandals and is lying prostrate. The strategy comes in chapter 6, but only after the posture of chapter 5 — the warrior on his face, the commander in charge, the ground recognized as holy."
